ont-weight:bold">Direct payment of Housing Costs to claimants</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">As</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">an organis</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ation supporting young people and promoting their independent living, we have grave concerns in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">respect of the proposal to make direct payment of Housing Costs to claimants. There are obvious concerns about the ability of people on very limited incomes to budget</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, especially for an entire month as per Universal Credit.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We are especially concerned </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">about direct payment of Housing Costs in view of our current experience of Jobcentre Plus’ use of sanctions in JSA and ESA claims</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> delays in the appeals process and administration of Hardship Payments where sanctions have been applied. Such delays will be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">inevitably increased when mandatory reconsideration </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">for JSA &amp; ESA </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">instituted from 28</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> October 13. In such cases it is unrealistic, indeed it would be arguably irrational, for claimants not to make use of their housing costs to meet their immediate subs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">istence needs.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Failure to meet rental charges </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">clearly will compromise </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">security of tenure and many claimants wil</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">l be vulnerable themselves or their household will include children and it is reasonably foreseeable that this will bring additional pressure to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> bear on statutory services including Social Care and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Housing Options.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Household Benefit Cap</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Whilst as an organisation, our service users have not been affected directly by the Benefit Cap, there are wider consequences including</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">locally</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the additional </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">pressure and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">consequent </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">tightening of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the eligibility criteria for Discretionary Housing Payments resulting in those cases which would previously have been considered meritorious being deemed of insufficient priority to qualify for an award.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">On a general </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">note,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> we feel that applying the Cap through the claimant’s Housing Benefit award </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">exacerbates</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the impact</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of the cut by prejudicing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the claimant and their household’s housing.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 66.02pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Social Sector Size Criteria</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The implementation of the social sector size criter</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ia has greatly added to the pressure upon the Discretionary Housing Payment scheme as per paragraph 4.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">As a supported housing provider our tenants are exempt from the SSSC. Hence, we frequently find our service users to be in the perverse position of enjo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ying better accommodation standards within supported accommodation than they can expect to achieve when moving on into their own independent tenancies</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in which we attempt to promote their having a vested interest</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. This is exacerbated by the abolition of So</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">cial Fund Community Care Grants</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> have ex</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">perience of several single</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> fathers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (with childcare responsibilities for children who spend the rest of the week with their other parent)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> who, prior to the implementation of the SSSC, were offered and accepted tw</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">o bedroom properties. These are young people who take their parental role seriously and are committed </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to taking an active part in their children’s lives. Downsizing will negatively impact upon their relationship with their children which is clearly undesir</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">able from both the individual a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nd a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> public policy</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> perspective.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There is a chronic shortage of smaller properties within the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Leeds</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> area which means that downsizing is simply not a realistic option for many people affected by the SSSC. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 66.02pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Localised Council Tax Support </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The localised Council Tax Support Scheme in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Leeds</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">has four protected groups who are able to qualify for 100% support in meeting their Council Tax liability. In effect, this means that most single people will have some contri</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">bution to make. Young people under 25 have an applicable amount of £14.90 per week less than that for a person over 25. For those people between 18 and 25, the required contribution to their Council Tax liability is causing acute financial hardship. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">financial hardship detailed above is increased where payments have not been made and the local authority have taken enforcement action through securing a Liability Order. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Leeds</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, this frequently means a debt of around £125 for the year being increased by</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> £90 costs.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Our service users are generally struggling to meet their contribution to their Council Tax due to limited income. However, this is frequently made worse through Jobcentre Plus’ application of sanctions at the current time. This is resulting i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">n a significant volume of people, who are often appealing sanction decisions, being left in acute financial hardship whilst being required to meet this additional liability.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> The above </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">points </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">reflect</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> a snapshot of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Gipsil</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> service user experience and we wou</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ld be happy to expand upon any issues should this be useful.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&